T1  - From Rubble to Respect at the "Ground Zero Mosque"
AN  - 1283643370; 201303250
AB  - "No fucking way!" As my father's profane words rang through our house, my adolescent mind reeled over what could cause such an outburst. Curiosity roused me from bed and, despite the early hour, I ran to the living room where my family had congregated around the TV. The images we were seeing -- the smoke and flames, the crumbling buildings, the fleeing civilians -- looked more like a scene from a Martin Scorsese film than breaking news coverage. That morning, we joined countless Americans who watched horror-struck, uncomprehending, as Arab terrorists shattered our seemingly impenetrable borders in the name of Islam. Meanwhile, employees of the Burlington Coat Factory in Lower Manhattan were no doubt also releasing curses that would have shocked my young ears. When American Airlines Flight 11 crashed into the north tower of the World Trade Center, a piece of the plane came loose, plunging through the roof of the outlet store located two blocks away. Although the ill-fated building at 51 Park Place remained vacant for the next two years, it would become the focus of a national ideological battle encompassing the mass confusion, biases, and cultural misunderstandings emerging in the wake of September 11, 2001. Adapted from the source document.
